Your job is to detect whether the given text is a dedicated Table of Contents (TOC) page.

A Table of Contents is a dedicated, clearly labeled section — typically titled "Contents", "Table of Contents", or similar — that lists the major sections or chapters of the entire document along with their page numbers or page references. It exists solely to help readers navigate the document and occupies a distinct block separate from the document body.

The following are NOT a Table of Contents:
- Section headings or numbered sections within the document body (e.g., "1. Introduction", "2. Methods")
- Abstract, summary, or executive summary sections
- Lists of figures, tables, algorithms, or symbols
- Keyword or topic lists
- Author affiliations, acknowledgements, or references
- An index at the back of the document

Important: Academic papers, journal articles, and conference papers almost never contain a Table of Contents. Only books, long technical reports, theses, or formal standards documents typically include one.

Given text: {{ content }}

Return the following JSON format:
{
    "toc_detected": "<yes or no>"
}

Directly return the final JSON structure. Do not output anything else.
